d","1140–Male":"1140–Afdød","1144–Female":"1144–Afdød","about 1182":"omkring 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"omkring 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"nl":{"about 1182–":"circa 1182–Overleden","1182–Male":"1182–Overleden","1182–Female":"1182–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1140–Male":"1140–Overleden","1144–Female":"1144–Overleden","about 1182":"circa 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"circa 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"en":{"about 1182–":"about 1182–Deceased","1182–Male":"1182–Deceased","1182–Female":"1182–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1144–Female":"1144–Deceased","about 1182":"about 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"about 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["(Welsh)  See  Llewelyn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewelyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Llywelyn ap Dafydd was born about 1182, in Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Dafydd ap Maredudd, of Caeo, was 44 and his mother, Mrs. Dafydd ap Maredudd of Caeo, was 40. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Llywelyn ap Dafydd."},"et":{"about 1182–":"umbes 1182–Surnud","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1182–Female":"1182–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1144–Female":"1144–Surnud","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1182–":"noin 1182–Kuollut","1182–Male":"1182–Kuollut","1182–Female":"1182–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1144–Female":"1144–Kuollut","about 1182":"noin 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"noin 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1182–":"environ 1182–Décédé","1182–Male":"1182–Décédé","1182–Female":"1182–Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1144–Female":"1144–Décédée","about 1182":"environ 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"environ 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Llywelyn ap Dafydd est né environ 1182, à Caio, Carmarthenshire, Galles, son père, Dafydd ap Maredudd, of Caeo, avait 44 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Dafydd ap Maredudd of Caeo, avait 40 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs. Llywelyn ap Dafydd."},"de":{"about 1182–":"um 1182–Verstorben","1182–Male":"1182–Verstorben","1182–Female":"1182–Verstorben","1200–Male":"1200–Verstorben","1140–Male":"1140–Verstorben","1144–Female":"1144–Verstorben","about 1182":"um 1182","1200":"1200","1144":"1144","about 1200":"um 1200","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Als Llywelyn ap Dafydd um 1182 in Caio, Carmarthenshire, Wales geboren wurde, war sein Vater Dafydd ap Maredudd, of Caeo 44 und seine Mutter Mrs. Dafydd ap Maredudd of Caeo 40. Er hatte mit Mrs. Llywelyn ap Dafydd mi